| ~~**B0 multishot recv + writev send**~~ | ~~Steady-state per-connection pattern~~ | **✅ shipped in `5b8a5d7`** — `arm_recv_multishot` (`IORING_OP_RECV` + `IORING_RECV_MULTISHOT`) + `submit_send` (`IORING_OP_SEND` + `MSG_NOSIGNAL`) + `submit_close` (`IORING_OP_CLOSE` + `IOSQE_CQE_SKIP_SUCCESS`); end-to-end echo round-trip verified live. |
| ~~**B0 static-path wire-in**~~ | ~~`HttpServer.serve_static` through `UringReactor`~~ | **✅ shipped in `3ae27e9`** — `run_uring_reactor_loop_static` is a functional twin of `run_reactor_loop_static` driven by `UringReactor` (multishot accept on the listener, multishot poll per conn fd). The static path's tight read→inline-send→read cycle never blocks between request arrivals, which is exactly the pattern multishot poll's edge-triggered semantics handle correctly. Live integration test (`tests/test_uring_serve_static.mojo`) confirms a real HTTP/1.1 GET round-trips through the io_uring stack on host kernel 6.8. **1/1 PASS**. |
| **B0 handler-path wire-in (poll-multishot attempt)** | `HttpServer.serve(handler)` + `Scheduler` workers through `UringReactor`'s `arm_poll_readable_multishot` (`IORING_OP_POLL_ADD` + `IORING_POLL_ADD_MULTI`). | **⚠️ attempted in `c8cd770`, reverted in `46addbd`**. The handler path's drain-then-block dispatch loses CQEs under sustained wrk2 load because multishot poll defaults to **edge-triggered**: a connection becomes readable, the dispatch drains via `recv-EAGAIN`, blocks on the next `io_uring_enter`, and if the next keep-alive request arrives between the drain and the enter the kernel observes no readiness *transition* (only "still ready"). No CQE is posted; the connection stalls. Empirically: epoll path serves 49 K req/s under `wrk2 -t4 -c64 -R50000`, the io_uring poll path serves 0 req/s on the exact same workload. |
| **B0 handler-path wire-in (recv-multishot attempt)** | Same wire-in but driven by `IORING_OP_RECV` (single-shot, re-armed per CQE) instead of poll. The kernel hands us bytes directly with no `poll → recv` round-trip and no edge-trigger race. Adds `ConnHandle.on_readable_from_buf[H]` (a bytes-driven parser entry, additive in commit `0116178`) plus `run_uring_recv_reactor_loop[H]` / `run_uring_recv_reactor_loop_shared[H]`. | **⚠️ attempted in `981eb8e`, reverted in `c6ccc79`**. Hit a deterministic ConnHandle lifecycle bug at exactly request #62 of every keep-alive client: `keepalive_count` resets to 0 with a new `ConnHandle` allocated at a different heap address (verified via instrumented `ch_addr` / `buf_addr` prints), the kernel-side socket fd is closed (peer's TCP state goes from ESTABLISHED to CLOSE without our cleanup path firing), and a genuine new `IORING_OP_ACCEPT` CQE fires for the same fd number. Best hypotheses: **(i)** Mojo's `var wire = self.write_buf^` move-out / move-back in `_serialize_response` interacts with the heap-allocated `Pool[ConnHandle]` slot in a way that runs the destructor mid-request, **(ii)** a Mojo runtime worker thread is racing on the per-conn recv buffer pointer pinned to the kernel SQE, or **(iii)** the kernel's per-fd recv arm has an internal limit we're hitting. Diagnosis was time-boxed; the fix path below sidesteps the bug entirely by removing the per-conn buffer pinning. `ConnHandle.on_readable_from_buf` (the additive parser entry from `0116178`) was kept in the tree as scaffolding for the next attempt. |
| **B0 zero-copy recv via buffer ring (the real fix)** | True multishot recv against a **kernel-managed buffer ring**: register a per-worker pool of N×64 KiB buffers via `IORING_REGISTER_BUFFERS` (or the simpler `IORING_OP_PROVIDE_BUFFERS`), set `IOSQE_BUFFER_SELECT` on the recv SQE plus `sqe->buf_group`, and arm a single `IORING_OP_RECV` + `IORING_RECV_MULTISHOT` per accepted fd. The kernel picks a buffer per CQE from the ring (buffer id in CQE's high 16 flag bits, decoded by `IoUringCqe.buffer_id()` which already exists), removes per-conn buffer pinning entirely, and matches what `tokio-uring` / `monoio` / `glommio` do for the same workload. | **v0.7.x scope**. Substrate to add: `arm_provide_buffers(group_id, count, size)` on `UringReactor`, plus a `BufferRing` struct that owns the kernel-side buffer pool. Then the dispatch becomes a one-line replacement of the failed `981eb8e` arm: `arm_recv_buffer_select(fd, buf_group, conn_id)` instead of `arm_recv_oneshot(fd, buf, len, conn_id)`. The buffer pinning that triggered the recv-multishot lifecycle bug goes away (no per-conn `recv_bufs[fd]`), and the syscall-per-request goes from 1 (recv) to 0 (everything is in the io_uring submit/complete flow). Estimated peak-throughput win on the 4-worker dev-box bench: closes the +30 % gap to `hyper` if combined with `submit_send` on the response side. |
| **EPYC publication** | Re-run `bench-vs-baseline` on EPYC 7R32 with the io_uring path enabled; refresh `benchmark/results/v0.7/iouring-vs-epoll/`. | Hardware-gated. The dev-box 4w bench (`46addbd`) sits at parity with the v0.6 EPYC peak on the epoll path (170 K vs 170 K) but the dev-box tail is dominated by 64-vCPU scheduler noise — the EPYC re-bench will publish the matched-worker / matched-cores numbers (which historically land at p99.99 = 3.11 ms; best-of-class). |

